metadata.name: Segments #251
metadata.description:
A continuous flowing motion of segmented cubes.

There is 5 routes for variations which is chosen by the 'Animation Type' variable. Each route then has it's own way to produce variety based on the random values injected into each.

Routes available (each is a type of noise used to change the animation of the cubes):
1. Waveform
2. Cellular
3. Voronoise
4. Polka Dots
5. Layers

Each route then has between 5 to 11 variables that will change the outcome of the overall look.

metadata.name: Seriscope Painting (2) #27
metadata.description:
Seriscope Paintings are composed via a generative printing process similar to serigraphy (silkscreen). A number of abstract paintings were produced traditionally using a paper marbling technique and used as a dataset to combine 4 single-colour halftone layers to make the image.

Seriscope paintings are generatively composed from a selection of:

40 Background (Who) Paintings
61 Midground (What) Paintings
61 Midground (Where) Paintings
81 Foreground (Why) Paintings

The title of each painting is also generatively composed at the time of mint within the attributes of the work - who, what, where and why.

Ryan Thompson, Jan 2022
@RT_Artwork

metadata.name: Quasiflock #250
metadata.description:
Quasiflock is a 2022 rework of a 2006 realtime animated generative system, originally one of the projects from which later my toxiclibs library collection and some other big client projects & brand identities grew out of. The piece was part of a long, multi-year investigation into particle systems, agents and the aesthetic of fluid dynamics. Even though the approach used here is very primitive, my overall aim was to create a dynamic (and minimally interactive/responsive) system, which is above all mesmerizing to watch and somewhat feels alive. Since the original Java/Processing version isn't able to run anymore, I did some major updates and ported it to Zig & WebAssembly to give it a new life, more fluidity and a larger audience. Hope you enjoy!

10 parametric color themes (each with variations)
10 macro design/behavioral params (to control dozens more)
optionally mouse/touch responsive (rotate/pulsate)...

Made w/ Zig, WASM & thi.ng/umbrella

metadata.name: Patched and Mended #101
metadata.description:
My previous Token "Patched" had an issue where different viewport sizes rendered slightly different outputs. At the time I was not able to correct this but now I am!
Patched and Mended has different palettes from the original, including a monochrome version, and doesn't have a resizing issue.
This is an airdrop and I have reserved all of the pieces allocating them to the current holders of Patched. When I added them all up there was one missing so I have allocated that to myself and if anyone finds they don't have an allocation do let me know and I'll hand it over.

metadata.name: Urban Inception Redux #150
metadata.description:
Urban Inception Redux borrows from the original Circle City project and goes bigger, 6x bigger to be exact, and adds a whole new alternate reality, more rings, and a new skew potential. 

PLEASE BE PATIENT - This project has a lot of computations and may take a minute or two to render. 

This project creates a 12 layer composition that can be exported as an SVG and plotted or used to cut a physical out of wood or acrylic using a laser. With each layer being a single contiguous element. 

More info about the project and physicals can be found at: 
https://alleditions.art/p/urban-inception-redux

Shift P - Export a PNG
Shift S - Export an SVG
Shift E - explode the layers

metadata.name: Murals #94
metadata.description:
'Murals' is a collection of 256 abstract compositions born out of an intense period diving deeply into street art, pointillism and the inner workings of neural networks.

The work explores projection, refraction and abstraction of points as they ripple through multi-dimensional space-time. Points refract through multi-dimensional space to become shapes, which then become coordinate systems for the projections of new points that create a sense of form, texture, lighting, and material properties. 

The work is also a celebration of imperfections and how a combination of many tiny – almost individually imperceptibly small – imperfect details can shape our perceptions of form, materiality, mood. This is explored within this work through subtle uses of sprays, flecks, scuffs, cuts, grain, targets (projections of projections), construction lines, base projections, occasional glitches that cause curvature, bounced light, shadows, and more.

Features:

15 colour palettes: 
Scream, Night Bus, Double Backflip, Jaws, Sunday, Atom, Space, Tipex, 
Graphite, Leaf, Earth, Bubble Gum, Citrus, Jellyfish, Damp Concrete.

4 times of day (that create subtle changes in light colour):
Daylight, Winter Morning, Midnight, Sunset

2 Border types: 
Normal, Thin

Various features that subtly impact appearance surface textures and shard forms:
Metallic, Engrave, Number of Shards, Scuff Marks, Symmetry. 

Controls:
- Press [ S ] to save the work at its current image size as a PNG.
- Press [ 1 ] to set the image size to 1440 x 1944 pixels (default size)
- Press [ 2 ] to set the image size to 2880 x 3888 pixels
- Press [ 3 ] to set the image size to 4320 x 5832 pixels

- Press [ F ] to toggle freeform mode to create custom image sizes and aspect ratios
- Press [ R ] to reload the image (for use in freeform mode)

This work has been tested on Chrome and Safari on Mac OS, and also using an Android smartphone. Please make sure that it works on your device before minting. Based on testing (in May 2022), each work should take about 5-10 seconds to fully load on a laptop or desktop machine, and 15-20 seconds on a mobile device. The loading process is animated so you can watch the construction the static artwork during this time. 

This artwork is created with p5.js 

@nbswwit, 2022

metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #212
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma // https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: Hexaëder #138
metadata.description:
Hexaëder (cube) is a research into abstraction and a search for a balance between simplification and visual complexity.

No matter how simple and unambiguous things appear to be, in reality they are often more complex. Enjoy the simple, explore the complex.

Hexaeder has a wide variety of possible outcomes. I have put together 10 different color palettes; the number of cubes ranges from 10 to 401 (18 different grids); each cell can have 4 different background patterns; each cube can be filled in 4 distinct ways; there are 5 line colors and 16 different "cube figures"; the vignette can be black or be the color of the palette, and there are several "texture settings". This results in over 1.8 million possibilities.

For more information see: https://www.behance.net/gallery/131114761/Hexaeder-Flattened-cubes

metadata.name: geometric tiles #32
metadata.description:
Hello everyone, this is my first fxhash project.

There are three types of mints you can get: checkers, stairs and rectangular prisms - there is equal chance of getting any of those. 

There is also 8% chance of getting the rarity mint which is the mint with the grainy effect over it. However, you should check my twitter out in order to see the preview of all the mint types you can get.

The inspiration behind this project was M.C. Escher.

metadata.name: Vormenspel #59
metadata.description:
Schetsboek contained an algorithm that scribbled a small piece of art (800x800 px).

In this artwork, I used that algorithm in two systems (in a grid and/or layered), taking it to new dimensions, but still focused on composition and the interplay of simple shapes and colors. 

It reminds me to stay playful and enjoy the little things in life.  

This is a free mint for holders of schetsboek.
